<i>- My name is Todd Andrews.</i>

00:16.391 --> 00:18.352
<i>I've been in the military,</i>
<i>in the Navy.</i>

00:18.352 --> 00:20.270
I have been a fireman.

00:20.270 --> 00:22.731
<i>I have worked on machinery.</i>

00:22.731 --> 00:24.566
<i>I'm hoping my experience</i>

00:24.566 --> 00:27.110
<i>will be the one thing</i>
<i>that helps me the most.</i>

00:27.110 --> 00:29.029
<i>- My name's DJ Morgan.</i>

00:29.029 --> 00:30.781
I am 22 years old.

00:30.781 --> 00:34.701
<i>I have been a ferrier</i>
<i>for three years.</i>

00:34.701 --> 00:36.411
At a young age,
I was in foster care,

00:36.411 --> 00:38.664
<i>and I didn't really have</i>
<i>many people to talk to.</i>

00:38.664 --> 00:40.207
I had a horse.

00:40.207 --> 00:41.750
I'd go out there,
I'd sit in his feeder,

00:41.750 --> 00:43.001
and I'd read a book to him.

00:43.001 --> 00:45.712
<i>- My name is Sam Troxel.</i>

00:45.712 --> 00:47.256
The major thing that
I'm nervous about

00:47.256 --> 00:50.175
is not knowing
what we'll be working on.

00:50.175 --> 00:52.886
But nervousness
means you have fear,

00:52.886 --> 00:55.097
and if you know that you have
fear, then you can overcome it.

00:55.097 --> 00:56.932
<i>- My name is Derick Romer.</i>

00:56.932 --> 00:58.725
<i>I started forging</i>
<i>out of necessity.</i>

00:58.725 --> 01:00.227
Eight years ago,
I lived in a yurt

01:00.227 --> 01:01.979
out in the backwoods of Oregon,

01:01.979 --> 01:05.232
<i>and I was doing repairs</i>
<i>on gardening implements</i>

01:05.232 --> 01:08.443
so that I could grow food
and feed myself.

01:08.443 --> 01:11.405
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:11.405 --> 01:13.991
You're here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:13.991 --> 01:15.409
of edged weapon-making
competition

01:15.409 --> 01:17.327
designed to push you
to your limit.

01:17.327 --> 01:19.246
At the end of each round,
you'll be presenting your work

01:19.246 --> 01:20.998
to our panel of expert judges.

01:20.998 --> 01:22.916
These are the men who decide
which of you will be

01:22.916 --> 01:24.501
our next "Forged in Fire"
champion

01:24.501 --> 01:26.336
and take home that check
for $10,000.

01:26.336 --> 01:28.213
Let's meet them now.

01:28.213 --> 01:30.299
Up first, two-time
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:30.299 --> 01:32.467
and fan favorite, Ben Abbott.

01:32.467 --> 01:35.387
Historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker.

01:35.387 --> 01:39.474
And last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:39.474 --> 01:41.268
All right, gentlemen,
on your anvils is a cloth.

01:41.268 --> 01:42.686
Go ahead and lift that up.

01:42.686 --> 01:49.693
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:49.693 --> 01:51.653
In the first round
of competition,

01:51.653 --> 01:54.197
you will be making signature
blades in your signature style

01:54.197 --> 01:56.783
from these slices
of elevator cable.

01:56.783 --> 01:59.911
- A giant chunk
of elevator cable.

01:59.911 --> 02:02.205
What the hell
am I gonna do with that?

02:02.205 --> 02:04.708
- Your blades must fall within
the following parameters:

02:04.708 --> 02:07.961
the length of your blade must
be between 9 and 12 inches

02:07.961 --> 02:10.005
and include a through tang.

02:10.005 --> 02:11.548
Keep in mind
that in the second round,

02:11.548 --> 02:13.759
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades

02:13.759 --> 02:15.594
to turn them into
fully functional weapons

02:15.594 --> 02:18.305
that will be tested for
strength and durability

02:18.305 --> 02:20.599
in a copper pipe baton chop

02:20.599 --> 02:23.644
and, for edge retention,
in an apple slice.

02:23.644 --> 02:25.437
You will have ten minutes
to work on your design.

02:25.437 --> 02:29.066
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

02:29.066 --> 02:30.192
Good luck, bladesmiths.

02:30.192 --> 02:31.985
Your time starts now.

02:31.985 --> 02:34.029
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:34.029 --> 02:36.448
- I think the biggest thing
getting started on these

02:36.448 --> 02:39.326
is to get that cable
welded up on both ends

02:39.326 --> 02:42.120
and twisted tight.

02:42.120 --> 02:43.163
- The type of knife
I'm designing

02:43.163 --> 02:44.831
is a basic skinning knife:

02:44.831 --> 02:47.834
<i>very utilitarian, very simple.</i>

02:47.834 --> 02:50.295
Just make a knife
that you feel comfortable with.

02:50.295 --> 02:54.508
I look at the future
and I see myself winning.

02:54.508 --> 02:57.302
I don't see myself losing.

02:57.302 --> 03:00.597
- I have not worked
with elevator cable,

03:00.597 --> 03:02.432
<i>but there's</i>
<i>a lot of properties</i>

03:02.432 --> 03:04.101
that I've learned in the past
that will help me out.

03:04.101 --> 03:07.396
<i>I'm choosing</i>
<i>a tanto-style blade.</i>

03:07.396 --> 03:09.523
<i>It's a long, thin blade,</i>

03:09.523 --> 03:13.944
and I have only a small amount
of useable cable in there

03:13.944 --> 03:15.070
<i>to make it a knife.</i>

03:16.863 --> 03:18.115
- What do you think
of this cable?

03:18.115 --> 03:19.449
- It works pretty quickly,

03:19.449 --> 03:21.910
but not with
stuff that's this dirty.

03:21.910 --> 03:24.955
- All the cleaning that needs
to be done individually,

03:24.955 --> 03:26.832
otherwise we're going to have
a lot of inclusions.

03:26.832 --> 03:30.335
- It's gonna be a challenge,
but I'm super-excited for it.

03:30.335 --> 03:33.839
<i>My plan right now is</i>
<i>to make a bowie-shaped knife.</i>

03:33.839 --> 03:36.508
<i>The bowie knife</i>
<i>is my go-to blade.</i>

03:36.508 --> 03:40.303
<i>- I need to make something</i>
<i>that is a good slicer,</i>

03:40.303 --> 03:43.014
but it also needs to be able
to wane on a copper pipe.

03:43.014 --> 03:45.016
<i>So what I'm designing</i>

03:45.016 --> 03:47.978
<i>is a variant of a Thai-style</i>
<i>knife called a narong.</i>

03:47.978 --> 03:51.440
- How in the world is Derick
going to use that sledgehammer?

03:51.440 --> 03:52.482
That's long.

03:52.482 --> 03:54.568
Gonna go like this.

03:54.568 --> 03:56.194
- Secure your cable,
gentlemen.

03:56.194 --> 03:59.197
Your three-hour forge time
starts...now.

03:59.197 --> 04:00.740
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:00.740 --> 04:02.742
First round of this competition

04:02.742 --> 04:05.078
is as much about
problem-solving

04:05.078 --> 04:07.998
as it is actual forging.

04:07.998 --> 04:10.542
We've given you
an odd-shaped piece of steel,

04:10.542 --> 04:13.378
but how you turn that
into the blade

04:13.378 --> 04:15.338
is entirely up to them.

04:15.338 --> 04:16.923
- You got to twist it

04:16.923 --> 04:18.800
to unravel the billet
on the inside

04:18.800 --> 04:21.678
and then go back in
and tighten it up again, right?

04:21.678 --> 04:23.555
- Once you get it hot,
twist it tight.

04:23.555 --> 04:26.558
Make that weld set.

04:26.558 --> 04:29.269
- My game plan is going to be
keep it simple,

04:29.269 --> 04:31.229
move forward
in a logical manner.

04:31.229 --> 04:33.482
<i>I'm just gonna take it apart,</i>

04:33.482 --> 04:35.942
<i>try to figure out exactly how</i>
<i>much cable I'm going to need.</i>

04:35.942 --> 04:38.653
One piece of cable
is not going to be enough.

04:38.653 --> 04:40.864
<i>I put two pieces in the forge.</i>

04:40.864 --> 04:42.699
- A smart move on Todd here

04:42.699 --> 04:45.577
to reduce the use of metal
that he has.

04:45.577 --> 04:47.579
<i>- I'm going to straighten</i>
<i>the cable out,</i>

04:47.579 --> 04:49.289
<i>and I'm going to start getting</i>
<i>it forge-welded</i>

04:49.289 --> 04:50.832
<i>and I'm going to start</i>
<i>getting it flat</i>

04:50.832 --> 04:52.125
<i>so I can deal with it better.</i>

04:52.125 --> 04:53.335
I'm very happy with it.

04:55.086 --> 04:59.925
- My game plan, first off,
is to get that bundle of cable

04:59.925 --> 05:01.968
<i>broken up</i>
<i>into smaller strands.</i>

05:01.968 --> 05:03.011
<i>It's greasy.</i>

05:03.011 --> 05:04.721
It has to be cleaned.

05:04.721 --> 05:07.933
- So Sam's actually
grabbed some cleaner.

05:07.933 --> 05:10.268
<i>- You got to get that oil off</i>
<i>or that can actually</i>

05:10.268 --> 05:12.646
be inclusions into your steel
once you get your pattern done.

05:12.646 --> 05:14.564
- Sam still looks great.

05:14.564 --> 05:16.691
It just looks piddly.

05:16.691 --> 05:18.485
There's not a whole lot
of it there.

05:18.485 --> 05:21.071
- I want to make sure
that that cable

05:21.071 --> 05:24.241
is staying together as tight
as bundled as it can.

05:24.241 --> 05:27.160
- If Sam can do the forge weld,
it's a nice strategy

05:27.160 --> 05:28.829
because it does start
with cleaner metal.

05:31.373 --> 05:32.999
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:32.999 --> 05:34.501
- My game plan is to burn off

05:34.501 --> 05:37.128
the oil and whatever
nasty is in there.

05:37.128 --> 05:39.047
- Now, you can see
there's a lot more flames

05:39.047 --> 05:40.507
coming out of his forge.

05:40.507 --> 05:42.300
Why is that?

05:42.300 --> 05:43.677
- The one thing
we didn't see from DJ

05:43.677 --> 05:45.512
was any big cleaning
of it.

05:45.512 --> 05:47.347
That's all that grease
burning off.

05:47.347 --> 05:48.890
- Burning the outside
then scrubbing it,

05:48.890 --> 05:50.600
it's not enough to do so

05:50.600 --> 05:51.893
because you got to get
inside the strands.

05:51.893 --> 05:53.311
- And he certainly
doesn't need

05:53.311 --> 05:56.982
that entire piece of cable
to make a blade.

05:56.982 --> 05:59.359
- I'm gonna get my cable
nice and hot,

05:59.359 --> 06:02.237
<i>get it as tight</i>
<i>as I possibly can.</i>

06:02.237 --> 06:03.947
At that point,
it'll start to forge weld.

06:05.365 --> 06:08.368
- When I do cable,
I weld both ends.

06:08.368 --> 06:10.829
That way,
it can't come apart.

06:10.829 --> 06:13.790
- Now you can just see all of
those little pieces coming off.

06:13.790 --> 06:15.667
<i>- It's not welding.</i>

06:15.667 --> 06:17.377
<i>I'm very stressed right now.</i>

06:17.377 --> 06:19.462
What did I get myself into?

06:19.462 --> 06:23.550
<i>[driving rock music]</i>

06:23.550 --> 06:26.219
<i>- My plan is to cut</i>
<i>that chunk of steel down.</i>

06:26.219 --> 06:27.679
<i>It's a huge amount of steel,</i>

06:27.679 --> 06:30.307
so I have
to weld the ends shut.

06:30.307 --> 06:31.850
<i>I have to get each</i>
<i>and every one of those</i>

06:31.850 --> 06:33.602
<i>little wires</i>
<i>to weld up properly,</i>

06:33.602 --> 06:35.437
<i>otherwise you get pretty</i>
<i>horrible delamination</i>

06:35.437 --> 06:37.272
that will spiral
through your blade.

06:37.272 --> 06:40.358
<i>You got to get flux</i>
<i>all inside that bundle</i>

06:40.358 --> 06:42.277
and avoid oxidation.

06:43.778 --> 06:45.906
- Oh, there ya go!

06:45.906 --> 06:48.950
<i>- I'm actually very glad</i>
<i>that this isn't my forge</i>

06:48.950 --> 06:51.953
because I'm going to flux
the crap out of this thing.

06:51.953 --> 06:55.165
- The forecast today
is flurries of flux.

06:55.165 --> 06:56.082
- [laughs]

06:58.084 --> 07:02.005
- Forging multiple layers of
steel is a very risky process.

07:02.005 --> 07:03.590
- So he's managed to get

07:03.590 --> 07:05.759
both of those pieces
welded together.

07:05.759 --> 07:07.886
He's back to
a nice-sized billet.

07:07.886 --> 07:10.430
One he starts rolling that out,
he should have plenty material.

07:10.430 --> 07:12.349
- When the metal
starts to move,

07:12.349 --> 07:15.477
<i>you go into, like,</i>
<i>a Zen kind of mindset.</i>

07:15.477 --> 07:17.646
<i>You become probably one person</i>
<i>within yourself.</i>

07:17.646 --> 07:19.564
It's like a runner's high,
almost.

07:19.564 --> 07:21.149
I'm in my zone.

07:21.149 --> 07:22.859
I'm gonna rock this thing.

07:22.859 --> 07:26.154
- Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

07:26.154 --> 07:27.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:27.572 --> 07:29.574
<i>- I've come up to a problem.</i>

07:29.574 --> 07:33.286
I see that my billet,
at this point, is too thin.

07:33.286 --> 07:34.954
Okay.

07:34.954 --> 07:36.414
<i>I know I have</i>
<i>to cut it in half</i>

07:36.414 --> 07:38.833
and forge weld it
back together.

07:38.833 --> 07:40.377
<i>I weld the two pieces together</i>

07:40.377 --> 07:43.171
and I'm off
to the forges again.

07:43.171 --> 07:45.048
<i>There's no pocketing.</i>

07:45.048 --> 07:48.301
That tells me I have
a knife in the running.

07:48.301 --> 07:49.636
- How's it going, buddy?

07:49.636 --> 07:51.471
- Going good, and you?

07:51.471 --> 07:53.473
- Not so good, but I'm going
to keep going with it.

07:53.473 --> 07:54.808
- Keep it up.

07:55.975 --> 07:58.853
- I am super stressed out.

07:58.853 --> 08:00.730
<i>I cut this open</i>
<i>with the chop saw,</i>

08:00.730 --> 08:03.233
<i>and nothing is welded.</i>

08:03.233 --> 08:04.734
- DJ looks like
he's not even working

08:04.734 --> 08:06.736
with as much material now.

08:06.736 --> 08:09.239
<i>- I'm just grabbing whatever</i>
<i>useable metal is left,</i>

08:09.239 --> 08:11.366
and I'm welding it together.

08:11.366 --> 08:13.201
I need to put my flux on it,

08:13.201 --> 08:16.287
get it back in the forge
until it gets up to the heat

08:16.287 --> 08:18.456
and then try
to press it together.

08:18.456 --> 08:21.418
<i>I don't have too much more</i>
<i>to work with.</i>

08:21.418 --> 08:24.546
<i>I used and ruined</i>
<i>a lot of other cable.</i>

08:24.546 --> 08:27.590
- All right, DJ is heading
over to the press right now.

08:27.590 --> 08:29.718
<i>- If I can't get this</i>
<i>forge-welded,</i>

08:29.718 --> 08:33.179
I am about as much as [bleep]
out of luck as it comes.

08:33.179 --> 08:34.139
- Oh, there he goes.

08:34.139 --> 08:35.413
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:38.685 --> 08:41.646
<i>[tense music]</i>

08:41.646 --> 08:45.525
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:45.525 --> 08:48.778
- It looks like DJ
managed to get a weld.

08:48.778 --> 08:50.822
- Heck yeah, I finally
got something to stick.

08:50.822 --> 08:52.157
- Is it going?

08:52.157 --> 08:54.242
- It's sticking.
- All right, man.

08:54.242 --> 08:56.286
- DJ seems to be
pretty happy with that.

08:56.286 --> 08:57.620
- Yep.

08:59.039 --> 09:00.915
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:00.915 --> 09:04.419
- I do see that
there are some defects

09:04.419 --> 09:06.046
