11:39.574 --> 11:41.492
<i>it can crack.</i>

11:41.492 --> 11:42.952
I'm hoping my heat treat
goes great

11:42.952 --> 11:45.788
because I have no time
for an error.

11:45.788 --> 11:48.750
<i>[tense music]</i>

11:48.750 --> 11:55.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:55.590 --> 11:57.717
- [scoffs]
- Ah.

11:57.717 --> 12:00.720
- Maybe nothing
could fracture at this point.

12:00.720 --> 12:04.432
- I am worried
that I might have cracks.

12:04.432 --> 12:06.309
Victory!

12:06.309 --> 12:07.727
- There you go!

12:07.727 --> 12:09.854
- All right.
[applause]

12:09.854 --> 12:11.689
It's in one piece
and it's straight.

12:11.689 --> 12:14.359
<i>I couldn't be any happier.</i>

12:14.359 --> 12:16.194
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

12:16.194 --> 12:18.529
- We still have one smith
that needs to quench,

12:18.529 --> 12:21.199
and by the end of this round,
I would really like to see

12:21.199 --> 12:23.326
those blades acid etched.

12:23.326 --> 12:25.536
And that way we can
see that pattern.

12:25.536 --> 12:28.373
<i>- The main operations left are</i>
<i>to go through heat treatment,</i>

12:28.373 --> 12:29.832
and a lot of things
can go wrong.

12:29.832 --> 12:32.001
<i>If there were</i>
<i>any delaminations,</i>

12:32.001 --> 12:33.962
<i>it could just blow apart</i>
<i>in the quench.</i>

12:36.506 --> 12:37.548
I pull the blade out.

12:37.548 --> 12:38.591
I take a quick look at it.

12:38.591 --> 12:40.593
I don't see any cracks.

12:40.593 --> 12:42.345
<i>I don't have much time</i>
<i>to grind.</i>

12:42.345 --> 12:43.388
<i>I still have to etch.</i>

12:44.973 --> 12:46.683
- Two minutes!

12:46.683 --> 12:49.394
<i>- I got to get this</i>
<i>in this acid bath.</i>

12:49.394 --> 12:51.396
I can't get the etch cap off.

12:51.396 --> 12:53.106
- Come on, kid,
you can do it!

12:53.106 --> 12:55.566
<i>[tense music]</i>

12:55.566 --> 12:56.651
- There you go.
- There you go.

12:56.651 --> 12:58.820
- Don't mind me.

12:58.820 --> 13:04.284
- 10, 9, 8, 7, 6,

13:04.284 --> 13:09.831
5, 4, 3, 2, 1!

13:09.831 --> 13:12.333
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

13:12.333 --> 13:15.837
Drop your tools. Pull your
blade out of that acid.

13:15.837 --> 13:17.630
This round is over.

13:17.630 --> 13:21.551
<i>- I wouldn't say I made</i>
<i>the prettiest knife,</i>

13:21.551 --> 13:24.304
but I definitely made
a functional, useable blade.

13:24.304 --> 13:26.222
- All right, bladesmiths,

13:26.222 --> 13:28.057
the first round
of competition is over.

13:28.057 --> 13:29.726
Now it's time for the judges

13:29.726 --> 13:32.020
to take a closer look
at what you've done.

13:32.020 --> 13:33.730
Todd, you're up first.

13:33.730 --> 13:36.024
Please present your steel
to the judges.

13:36.024 --> 13:37.442
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

13:37.442 --> 13:39.193
- Well, Todd, first off,

13:39.193 --> 13:40.820
I like the trailing point
that you have here.

13:40.820 --> 13:43.781
It feels like definitely
a blade that likes to slash.

13:43.781 --> 13:45.533
The only concern is that
there's a little bit

13:45.533 --> 13:47.869
of some delaminations
on the side of the blade here,

13:47.869 --> 13:49.537
but at least it's on the side,
and you can grind that out.

13:49.537 --> 13:50.913
- Ouch.

13:50.913 --> 13:52.248
- But overall, solid work.

13:52.248 --> 13:53.332
Good job.

13:53.332 --> 13:55.209
- Thank you.

13:55.209 --> 13:57.462
- All right, DJ, please present
your work to the judges.

13:59.130 --> 14:00.298
- Well, DJ, you had me sweating
in the beginning,

14:00.298 --> 14:01.841
that's for sure.

14:01.841 --> 14:03.551
That cable was kicking
your butt, man.

14:03.551 --> 14:05.094
- Oh, yeah.

14:05.094 --> 14:06.888
- There's a couple
small delaminations.

14:06.888 --> 14:08.431
There's one here at the edge

14:08.431 --> 14:09.974
and then there's
some at the spine

14:09.974 --> 14:11.809
that doesn't look very deep.

14:11.809 --> 14:13.311
There's a lot of mass here,
though,

14:13.311 --> 14:15.021
so there's a lot of room
for grinding.

14:15.021 --> 14:17.523
After all that impediment
you started with,

14:17.523 --> 14:19.108
you turned in a solid blade.

14:19.108 --> 14:20.443
- Thank you.

14:20.443 --> 14:21.360
- All right, Sam, you're up.

14:21.360 --> 14:23.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:23.654 --> 14:27.241
- This blade, it's already
just smooth as can be.

14:27.241 --> 14:30.828
I really like the prep work
you did to get this done.

14:30.828 --> 14:34.332
The concern I have
is this spiral delamination

14:34.332 --> 14:37.835
of that one wire that runs
around and around and around.

14:37.835 --> 14:39.796
And I don't know
how deep that runs.

14:39.796 --> 14:41.380
- All right, Derick,

14:41.380 --> 14:42.632
please present
your blade to the judges.

14:42.632 --> 14:44.675
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:44.675 --> 14:46.385
- Well, Derick, I like
the shape of your blade.

14:46.385 --> 14:47.845
I think it's cool.

14:47.845 --> 14:50.556
On the blade,
there's a bit of a warp.

14:50.556 --> 14:52.934
But on the tang,
there's a lot of a warp.

14:52.934 --> 14:56.354
I mean, you can--
you can see it.

14:56.354 --> 14:58.898
There's a lot
of tang here,

14:58.898 --> 15:00.650
which puts you in a position

15:00.650 --> 15:02.985
that you can do anything
you want with the tang.

15:02.985 --> 15:05.321
- All right, bladesmiths,

15:05.321 --> 15:06.864
you've heard
the judges' critiques,

15:06.864 --> 15:08.991
but I have to get
their final decision.

15:08.991 --> 15:10.493
So while we go
into deliberation

15:10.493 --> 15:13.079
please step off
The Forge floor.

15:13.079 --> 15:16.082
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

15:16.082 --> 15:17.375
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:17.375 --> 15:18.918
- Oh, guys,
here we go, ah?

15:18.918 --> 15:20.503
- Yeah.

15:20.503 --> 15:22.130
- All right, judges,

15:22.130 --> 15:23.798
our bladesmiths
have turned in their work.

15:23.798 --> 15:25.174
Let's get into the details.

15:25.174 --> 15:26.926
We're gonna start
with Todd's blade.

15:26.926 --> 15:29.595
<i>- I like Todd's shape.</i>

15:29.595 --> 15:31.347
<i>You know, it's solid.</i>

15:31.347 --> 15:33.349
You can see how it gets fat
towards the tip.

15:33.349 --> 15:34.892
And he's kind of lucky that
that happened

15:34.892 --> 15:36.686
because of that delamination.

15:36.686 --> 15:38.312
Now, he could, just by grinding
on that one side,

15:38.312 --> 15:41.274
get that delam out of there.

15:41.274 --> 15:44.819
- Let's move on to our next
bladesmith, and that is DJ.

15:44.819 --> 15:47.989
<i>- DJ put in some good work.</i>

15:47.989 --> 15:49.657
<i>If you look at these delams,</i>

15:49.657 --> 15:52.160
you can actually see them
fold over the back.

15:52.160 --> 15:54.954
But you don't see them travel
down the side of the blade,

15:54.954 --> 15:56.455
either from the edge
or from the spine,

15:56.455 --> 15:58.124
and that's a good thing.

15:58.124 --> 16:01.752
- Let's move on
to our next bladesmith, Sam.

16:01.752 --> 16:04.672
<i>- When you look at</i>
<i>Sam's blade,</i>

16:04.672 --> 16:06.424
it mimics the way
he was working out there,

16:06.424 --> 16:09.051
very cool,
everything was controlled.

16:09.051 --> 16:10.887
You can see the beautiful
patterns here,

16:10.887 --> 16:14.015
but if you follow the lines,
it all leads to cracks.

16:14.015 --> 16:16.934
And we're gonna say, "Well,
maybe he can grind them out."

16:16.934 --> 16:19.562
No, this is thin because
he's been grinding on this.

16:19.562 --> 16:22.857
I don't think any more grinding
is gonna fix it.

16:22.857 --> 16:24.066
- Let's move on to Derick.

16:25.693 --> 16:27.528
<i>- His steel looks</i>
<i>pretty solid.</i>

16:27.528 --> 16:29.280
I don't see
any major delaminations

16:29.280 --> 16:30.573
or anything like that.

16:30.573 --> 16:32.450
It is heavy, though.

16:32.450 --> 16:34.452
There is a slight warp
in the blade

16:34.452 --> 16:35.995
that I think can be mitigated

16:35.995 --> 16:39.457
with some grinding
on this side here.

16:39.457 --> 16:40.458
- Doug, have you made
your final decision?

16:40.458 --> 16:41.417
- Yes, I have.
- Dave?

16:41.417 --> 16:42.376
- Oh, yeah.

16:42.376 --> 16:43.544
- Ben?
- Yes.

16:43.544 --> 16:46.005
- Let's go tell our smiths.

16:46.005 --> 16:48.758
Bladesmiths, in the first round
of competition,

16:48.758 --> 16:51.552
we gave you the challenge of
using twists of elevator cable

16:51.552 --> 16:53.596
from which
to forge your blades.

16:53.596 --> 16:57.016
But for one of you, the ride
stops right here on this floor.

16:57.016 --> 16:59.977
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

16:59.977 --> 17:02.355
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:02.355 --> 17:04.523
Sam, your blade
didn't make the cut.

17:06.317 --> 17:08.486
- Sam, your blade had
those spiral delaminations

17:08.486 --> 17:10.029
going all the way along it,

17:10.029 --> 17:12.031
and they would need
to be ground out.

17:12.031 --> 17:14.533
However, your blade
is already about as thin

17:14.533 --> 17:16.077
as we'd like to see it.

17:16.077 --> 17:18.162
For that reason,
we're sending you home.

17:18.162 --> 17:20.665
- Sam, please
surrender your blade.

17:20.665 --> 17:22.458
<i>- I definitely agree</i>

17:22.458 --> 17:24.377
<i>that the judges</i>
<i>made a good call on that.</i>

17:24.377 --> 17:28.506
Most likely, there was
something in the steel

17:28.506 --> 17:30.424
<i>or something</i>
<i>I put into the steel</i>

17:30.424 --> 17:32.635
to cause the delamination.

17:32.635 --> 17:34.178
<i>I've learned a lot.</i>

17:34.178 --> 17:36.264
I definitely
don't feel good about it,

17:36.264 --> 17:39.600
<i>but I feel that not all</i>
<i>learning experiences are good.</i>

17:42.687 --> 17:45.189
- Bladesmiths,
congratulations.

17:45.189 --> 17:47.733
You've made it into the second
round of this competition,

17:47.733 --> 17:49.527
and now that those blades
have been tempered,

17:49.527 --> 17:52.071
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

17:52.071 --> 17:53.906
by attaching handles to them.

17:53.906 --> 17:55.283
Now, in the first round,

17:55.283 --> 17:58.703
we gave you twists
of elevator cable

17:58.703 --> 18:00.371
from which
to forge your blades.

18:00.371 --> 18:02.164
In the second round,

18:02.164 --> 18:04.834
we want a twist in the handles
of your blades.

18:04.834 --> 18:07.795
<i>You must include</i>
<i>a spiral handle in addition</i>

18:07.795 --> 18:10.298
<i>to a guard and pommel</i>
<i>on your blades.</i>

18:10.298 --> 18:12.341
You'll have three hours
in this round.

18:12.341 --> 18:14.302
At the end of this round,
each of your weapons

18:14.302 --> 18:15.970
will be tested for strength
and durability

18:15.970 --> 18:18.681
in a copper pipe baton chop

18:18.681 --> 18:22.101
and for edge retention
in an apple slice.

18:22.101 --> 18:23.686
Good luck, bladesmiths.

18:23.686 --> 18:25.855
Your three hours starts now.

18:25.855 --> 18:27.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:27.982 --> 18:30.484
So we threw 'em a twist
in the first round.

18:30.484 --> 18:32.570
In the second round,
we want a twisted handle

18:32.570 --> 18:35.114
as well as a guard
and a pommel.

18:35.114 --> 18:37.617
So these guys have
a lot of work to do here.

18:37.617 --> 18:40.870
I think the most work has
to be done by Derick over here.

18:40.870 --> 18:43.122
He's got a big, beefy,
rusty blade right now.

18:43.122 --> 18:44.999
- Yep.

18:44.999 --> 18:49.211
- I survived, but I have
a [bleep] load of work to do.

18:49.211 --> 18:51.213
<i>I want to correct</i>
<i>the warp on the tang</i>

18:51.213 --> 18:53.174
<i>before I remove meat</i>
<i>on the tang.</i>

18:53.174 --> 18:55.843
Correcting a warp
is potentially disastrous.

18:55.843 --> 18:57.762
To ensure I don't
crack the blade,

18:57.762 --> 18:59.889
<i>I wrap it in a whole bunch</i>
<i>of wet paper towels</i>

18:59.889 --> 19:01.807
'cause that will absorb
heat from the torch.

19:01.807 --> 19:05.019
<i>As long as I keep that heat</i>
<i>right where I need it,</i>

19:05.019 --> 19:07.897
<i>it will not crack.</i>

19:07.897 --> 19:12.234
I will not crack this blade
'cause I know what I'm doing.

19:14.070 --> 19:17.490
- Trying to accomplish a buck
guard, a scrolled handle,

19:17.490 --> 19:19.241
<i>all of the corrections</i>
<i>that the judges wanted--</i>

19:19.241 --> 19:20.993
<i>I'm not really sure</i>

19:20.993 --> 19:22.370
<i>I can get everything done</i>
<i>in three hours.</i>

19:22.370 --> 19:24.497
- What is the RPM range
on these things?

19:24.497 --> 19:26.040
- 7,600 RPM.

19:26.040 --> 19:28.751
The circumference is pi D,

19:28.751 --> 19:30.920
so 8 times 3 is 24,

19:30.920 --> 19:33.047
so two feet every time
it turns one.

19:33.047 --> 19:35.758
That's about 15,000 feet
per minute.

19:35.758 --> 19:38.427
- You're getting math on me.
Stop it.

19:38.427 --> 19:41.263
<i>- I've never made</i>
<i>a spiral handle before.</i>

19:41.263 --> 19:44.475
<i>Material I'm working with,</i>
<i>bone, it's a little forgiving.</i>

19:44.475 --> 19:46.435
<i>When the impact</i>
<i>of the chop happens,</i>

19:46.435 --> 19:49.689
<i>hopefully I won't have my</i>
<i>guard or my pommel pop off.</i>

19:49.689 --> 19:52.733
I'm giving it my best shot,
and I'm going to move forward.

19:52.733 --> 19:55.361
- I want to get
my handle put together

19:55.361 --> 19:57.571
before I start to really work
on my blade

19:57.571 --> 20:00.074
so I have time for glue to dry.

20:00.074 --> 20:03.035
So my plan is to have
a threaded tang

20:03.035 --> 20:06.205
<i>so I can tighten it down and</i>
<i>make everything super tight.</i>

20:06.205 --> 20:08.874
Why is this not going on?

20:08.874 --> 20:10.960
- My guard,
it's just way too loose.

20:10.960 --> 20:13.003
It's just not going to work.

20:13.003 --> 20:15.047
So I have to start over rather
than try to salvage that one.

20:15.047 --> 20:17.299
<i>A loose guard</i>
<i>might crack the handle.</i>

20:17.299 --> 20:19.385
<i>Mine just fell apart.</i>

20:19.385 --> 20:21.929
<i>I'm a little behind</i>
<i>as far as time.</i>

20:21.929 --> 20:24.849
<i>It's better than the last one</i>
<i>but still loose.</i>

20:24.849 --> 20:27.727
It doesn't fit
as well as I would like,

20:27.727 --> 20:29.520
<i>but I'm going</i>
<i>to use it anyway.</i>

20:29.520 --> 20:32.440
- Bladesmiths!
Half the time is gone

20:32.440 --> 20:34.316
in this second round
of competition.

20:34.316 --> 20:36.277
<i>- Starting to feel</i>
<i>a time crunch.</i>

20:36.277 --> 20:38.362
<i>I want to grind this off,</i>
<i>get it sharp,</i>

20:38.362 --> 20:41.240
and getting the butt cap on
is a piece of cake.

20:41.240 --> 20:44.660
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:44.660 --> 20:47.913
Like, the weld
heats the epoxy too much,

20:47.913 --> 20:50.791
and the whole
butt cap lifts off

20:50.791 --> 20:54.086
<i>and my epoxy's</i>
<i>catching on fire.</i>

20:54.086 --> 20:56.046
- Oh, that don't look good.

20:56.046 --> 20:57.632
- No.

21:01.177 --> 21:03.596
<i>- So I welded the butt cap on,</i>
<i>right,</i>

21:03.596 --> 21:06.098
<i>but doing so, the heat caused</i>
<i>the butt cap to come loose,</i>

21:06.098 --> 21:08.601
<i>so there's about 1/8 inch gap,</i>

21:08.601 --> 21:12.146
<i>so I just shoved a whole bunch</i>
<i>of superglue in there.</i>

21:12.146 --> 21:14.273
<i>Fill that gap,</i>
<i>I think I got it.</i>

21:14.273 --> 21:16.400
I need to get
this pinhole drilled,

21:16.400 --> 21:18.110
but ironwood is really brittle,

21:18.110 --> 21:20.946
so, uh, I could split
the handle right now.

21:20.946 --> 21:21.947
This is gonna really suck.

21:21.947 --> 21:23.741
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:23.741 --> 21:26.452
- So threading my tang
is not working.

21:26.452 --> 21:28.579
<i>I decide</i>
<i>to just glue my handle</i>

21:28.579 --> 21:30.206
and weld the butt cap
onto the tang.

21:30.206 --> 21:33.000
<i>But I have too much glue</i>
<i>on my handle,</i>

21:33.000 --> 21:35.377
<i>and my tang is not fitting.</i>

21:35.377 --> 21:37.588
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:37.588 --> 21:40.549
- DJ's scraping the epoxy off
in case it dries too fast.

21:40.549 --> 21:43.135
<i>- I'm trying my best</i>
<i>to keep calm,</i>

21:43.135 --> 21:46.263
and I re-add adhesive to it.

21:47.306 --> 21:50.476
- DJ just took the black
section of the epoxy

21:50.476 --> 21:53.187
and just poured it around
the gap at the top.

21:53.187 --> 21:54.939
Just the black section, as if--

21:54.939 --> 21:57.149
- It's harder.
It makes things harder.

21:57.149 --> 21:58.943
- Yeah, you kind of
need them both together

21:58.943 --> 22:02.571
or it doesn't dry.
- Oh, no wonder.

22:02.571 --> 22:07.701
<i>- I have to make sure that</i>
<i>I have enough etching time.</i>

22:07.701 --> 22:10.871
A knife looks so much better
with the edge etched.

22:10.871 --> 22:12.206
It's what I want.
It's what I like.

22:12.206 --> 22:14.333
<i>I pull the knife</i>
<i>out of the acid</i>

22:14.333 --> 22:17.378
<i>and I see a very tight</i>
<i>woven pattern.</i>

22:17.378 --> 22:19.255
That's exactly what you want.

22:19.255 --> 22:21.131
<i>When you're gonna</i>
<i>go through testing,</i>

22:21.131 --> 22:23.425
<i>you want to make sure</i>
<i>that your knife is as tight</i>

22:23.425 --> 22:25.719
and as close together
as you can get.

22:25.719 --> 22:29.014
- There is, like,
five minutes left,

22:29.014 --> 22:31.851
<i>and it's not sharp.</i>

22:31.851 --> 22:36.105
I don't like doing my final
sharpening on a belt grinder.

22:36.105 --> 22:37.064
- What is Derick doing now?

22:37.064 --> 22:38.691
- Shut up.

22:38.691 --> 22:41.902
He has been wearing,
all day, a tungsten ring.

22:41.902 --> 22:44.071
- I know that this
is tungsten carbide.

22:44.071 --> 22:46.949
<i>I know that</i>
<i>pull-through sharpeners</i>

22:46.949 --> 22:49.618
<i>are generally</i>
<i>made of some form of carbide,</i>

22:49.618 --> 22:54.123
so I create a simple improvised
pull-through sharpener.

22:54.123 --> 22:56.500
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:56.500 --> 22:58.961
- So this guy
has taken his two rings,

22:58.961 --> 23:02.840
put them side by side
in the vice so they're touching

23:02.840 --> 23:06.552
and he's using the gap
to sharpen his blade.

23:06.552 --> 23:07.845
<i>- I see hairs.</i>

23:07.845 --> 23:09.138
<i>It's sharp enough.</i>

23:09.138 --> 23:12.266
I did it.

23:12.266 --> 23:14.894
- So far, I got the twist
in my handle.

23:14.894 --> 23:16.812
For what I've got going on,

23:16.812 --> 23:18.439
I think
I'm sitting pretty good.

23:18.439 --> 23:22.568
<i>I'm trying to grind</i>
<i>my hand safety</i>

23:22.568 --> 23:25.070
<i>into a better design</i>
<i>than just a rectangle.</i>

23:25.070 --> 23:28.073
<i>As I'm pushing it onto</i>
<i>the grinder, it spins.</i>

23:28.073 --> 23:30.159
It is loose.

23:30.159 --> 23:33.120
I'm screwed.
- Two minutes!

23:33.120 --> 23:34.997
<i>- My stomach drops.</i>

23:34.997 --> 23:37.666
If my fit is not tight enough,
I will get disqualified.

23:37.666 --> 23:39.168
<i>Quitting is not an option.</i>

23:39.168 --> 23:42.379
<i>I am gonna pass out</i>
<i>or someone else</i>

23:42.379 --> 23:44.965
is going to tell me to stop
because I do not quit.

23:44.965 --> 23:49.720
- Five, four, three, two, one.

23:49.720 --> 23:51.180
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

23:51.180 --> 23:52.765
Drop your tools.

23:52.765 --> 23:55.351
This second round
of competition is over.

23:55.351 --> 23:57.394
[applause]

23:57.394 --> 23:58.896
<i>- One concern of the judges</i>
<i>I didn't fix entirely</i>

23:58.896 --> 24:00.731
was the inclusion
at the tip of the blade.

24:00.731 --> 24:02.441
<i>I think that</i>
<i>the tip of the blade</i>

24:02.441 --> 24:04.318
<i>isn't going to be used</i>
<i>at the testing.</i>

24:04.318 --> 24:07.529
I've done what I could do
and now it's up to the judges.

24:07.529 --> 24:09.949
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test.

24:09.949 --> 24:12.451
To test the strength
and durability of your blades,

24:12.451 --> 24:15.412
I am going to be bashing
your knives with a baton

24:15.412 --> 24:18.582
into these copper pipes
mercilessly.

24:18.582 --> 24:20.209
Remember, this test
is all about

24:20.209 --> 24:22.002
what the pipes
do to your blades

24:22.002 --> 24:24.004
and not what your blades
do to the pipes.

24:24.004 --> 24:25.381
Todd, you're up first.
Are you ready?

24:25.381 --> 24:26.423
- I am.

24:26.423 --> 24:28.759
- Excellent.

24:28.759 --> 24:30.344
<i>- I'm starting</i>
<i>to sweat pretty hard.</i>

24:30.344 --> 24:32.721
<i>I'm hoping</i>
<i>he doesn't swing hard,</i>

24:32.721 --> 24:34.890
but Ben's not gonna
hold back.

24:34.890 --> 24:35.933
He never would.

24:35.933 --> 24:39.478
<i>It's going to be rough.</i>

24:39.478 --> 24:42.564
<i>[hard driving music]</i>

24:42.564 --> 24:49.488
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:58.831 --> 25:01.041
- Ouch.

25:01.041 --> 25:04.253
- Well, Todd, we've got
six edge deflections here.

25:04.253 --> 25:05.963
<i>Each side of the pipe</i>

25:05.963 --> 25:07.881
<i>took a little nibble</i>
<i>out of your blade.</i>

25:07.881 --> 25:09.633
But it all stayed in one piece.

25:09.633 --> 25:11.301
Nothing broke loose,
so good job.

25:11.301 --> 25:12.302
- Thrilled.

25:12.302 --> 25:13.846
[laughter]

25:13.846 --> 25:14.930
- DJ, you're up.

25:14.930 --> 25:17.599
- Hit it with all you got.

25:17.599 --> 25:20.519
<i>When I see the damage that</i>
<i>has been done to Todd's blade,</i>

25:20.519 --> 25:22.396
<i>I'm very nervous.</i>

25:22.396 --> 25:24.273
<i>If his looks like that,</i>

25:24.273 --> 25:26.025
I wonder what the heck
mine's gonna turn out like.

25:28.652 --> 25:31.530
<i>[hard driving music]</i>

25:31.530 --> 25:38.495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:47.546 --> 25:50.841
- Well, DJ, your blade
held up relatively well.

25:50.841 --> 25:53.260
There's a little bit of
deflection here at the blade,

25:53.260 --> 25:55.304
but there's a big problem.

26:00.017 --> 26:03.479
This is some
brittle handle material.

26:03.479 --> 26:06.982
And it's still sticky.
- Oh, boy.

26:06.982 --> 26:08.859
- When you were
mixing the epoxy,

26:08.859 --> 26:10.486
I thought for a minute
that I saw you

26:10.486 --> 26:12.237
just putting in the hardener

26:12.237 --> 26:15.199
without any
of the epoxy itself.

26:15.199 --> 26:19.119
- DJ, we cannot continue
with testing with your blade.

26:19.119 --> 26:22.998
However, this weapons test
is not over.

26:22.998 --> 26:27.044
Derick, your blade
has to survive all nine licks

26:27.044 --> 26:28.587
against this copper pipe.

26:28.587 --> 26:29.963
How you feeling right now?

26:29.963 --> 26:32.174
- Do it.
I love destructive testing.

26:33.926 --> 26:35.469
<i>I still have</i>
<i>to get through this test.</i>

26:35.469 --> 26:37.679
<i>The same thing</i>
<i>could happen to my blade</i>

26:37.679 --> 26:39.598
because I was light
on the epoxy

26:39.598 --> 26:41.725
<i>or my blade could shatter.</i>

26:41.725 --> 26:44.728
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

26:44.728 --> 26:51.735
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:59.785 --> 27:01.161
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:01.161 --> 27:03.288
- Derick, unfortunately,

27:03.288 --> 27:06.291
you suffered
a catastrophic blade failure

27:06.291 --> 27:08.585
after only five strikes
on the copper pipe.

27:08.585 --> 27:11.755
You cannot continue with
testing, and for that reason,

27:11.755 --> 27:15.134
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

27:15.134 --> 27:17.219
- Hey, it was so great,
yeah.

27:17.219 --> 27:18.595
<i>I might have heat treated</i>
<i>a bit hot.</i>

27:18.595 --> 27:20.639
I was in a real rush
in round one.

27:20.639 --> 27:24.685
I think I did the best I could
in the time that was given me.

27:24.685 --> 27:27.729
<i>I was kind of stressed</i>
<i>on the floor,</i>

27:27.729 --> 27:30.148
but, truthfully,
it was wonderful.

27:30.148 --> 27:32.484
<i>I loved it.</i>

27:32.484 --> 27:34.945
- Todd, DJ, congratulations.

27:34.945 --> 27:36.738
You've made it into the final
round of this competition.

27:36.738 --> 27:38.740
Now we're sending you
back to your home forges

27:38.740 --> 27:41.702
to re-create an iconic weapon
from history.

27:41.702 --> 27:43.078
That weapon is...

27:43.078 --> 27:46.623
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:46.623 --> 27:48.292
the landsknecht sword.

27:50.836 --> 27:52.462
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:52.462 --> 27:54.381
<i>Created by</i>
<i>Emperor Maximilian I</i>

27:54.381 --> 27:56.216
<i>in the 15th century,</i>

27:56.216 --> 27:57.843
<i>the landsknechts</i>
<i>were a deadly mercenary force</i>

27:57.843 --> 28:00.470
<i>armed with pikes, swords,</i>
<i>and crossbows.</i>

28:00.470 --> 28:02.848
<i>The most battle-proven</i>
<i>landsknecht mercenaries</i>

28:02.848 --> 28:05.142
<i>were armed with massive</i>
<i>two-handed swords.</i>

28:05.142 --> 28:08.228
<i>These imposing blades featured</i>
<i>parrying lugs above the guard</i>

28:08.228 --> 28:10.731
<i>to deflect enemy attacks.</i>

28:10.731 --> 28:12.649
<i>Earning double the pay</i>
<i>of their peers,</i>

28:12.649 --> 28:15.235
<i>these garishly dressed</i>
<i>swordsmen of fortune</i>

28:15.235 --> 28:17.154
<i>would rush headlong</i>
<i>into enemy pikes</i>

28:17.154 --> 28:19.781
<i>in an effort to disrupt</i>
<i>their opponents' formations.</i>

28:19.781 --> 28:22.326
<i>Due to its formidable size</i>
<i>and bloody reputation,</i>

28:22.326 --> 28:24.036
<i>the landsknecht sword lives on</i>

28:24.036 --> 28:25.871
<i>in a variety of movies</i>
<i>and video games,</i>

28:25.871 --> 28:29.791
<i>including</i>
<i>"The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim."</i>

28:29.791 --> 28:32.210
The blade parameters
are as follows:

28:32.210 --> 28:36.465
you must have two parrying lugs
leading to a guard.

28:36.465 --> 28:39.509
The length of the blade must be
between 34 and 36 inches

28:39.509 --> 28:41.929
and must be at least
two inches wide.

28:41.929 --> 28:43.639
You will have five days
at your home forges

28:43.639 --> 28:45.682
in which to complete
this blade.

28:45.682 --> 28:48.518
At the end of those five days,
you will return to this forge

28:48.518 --> 28:51.271
and present your blades
to our panel of expert judges,

28:51.271 --> 28:53.941
and only after they've tested
the twisted hell out of them

28:53.941 --> 28:56.443
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

28:56.443 --> 28:58.862
who leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

28:58.862 --> 29:00.238
Good luck, bladesmiths.

29:00.238 --> 29:01.239
We'll see you in five days.

29:01.239 --> 29:02.491
- Good luck to you, brother.

29:02.491 --> 29:03.825
- Yes, good luck to you too.

29:03.825 --> 29:05.786
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:05.786 --> 29:07.913
<i>It's the beginning of day one.</i>

29:07.913 --> 29:09.915
<i>I have never made anything</i>
<i>like this, but I'm excited.</i>

29:09.915 --> 29:12.042
Let's do it.

29:12.042 --> 29:16.004
<i>My plan today is to start</i>
<i>to draw some of my material</i>

29:16.004 --> 29:17.631
so I can have a better idea

29:17.631 --> 29:20.217
of how long
I'm gonna be able to make this.

29:20.217 --> 29:22.886
That is gonna be a long one.

29:22.886 --> 29:26.306
<i>Me not using any power tools,</i>

29:26.306 --> 29:29.726
<i>I do believe that it's gonna</i>
<i>cause me to be more fatigued,</i>

29:29.726 --> 29:31.520
but this is "Forged in Fire."

29:31.520 --> 29:33.188
It's not
"Power Hammer in Fire."

29:33.188 --> 29:35.107
<i>I'm done with day one.</i>

29:35.107 --> 29:36.650
<i>My hands are pretty sore.</i>

29:36.650 --> 29:38.193
I'm gonna go
and probably ice them

29:38.193 --> 29:39.695
so they're good to go
for tomorrow.

29:39.695 --> 29:42.572
Heck yeah, good first day.

29:42.572 --> 29:44.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:44.491 --> 29:46.201
<i>- It's day one.</i>

29:46.201 --> 29:47.953
<i>The weapon that I've been</i>
<i>challenged with</i>

29:47.953 --> 29:50.956
is a langersknecht--

29:50.956 --> 29:52.833
langersknet.

29:52.833 --> 29:54.918
It's a big, huge German word.

29:54.918 --> 29:58.463
<i>I want to work on some of</i>
<i>the accessory pieces first.</i>

29:58.463 --> 30:00.757
<i>One of them will be a cable</i>
<i>of Damascus.</i>

30:00.757 --> 30:02.926
The Damascus guard is going
to be the centerpiece

30:02.926 --> 30:04.511
of the whole sword.

30:04.511 --> 30:05.762
<i>I go weld</i>
<i>the end of the cable.</i>

30:05.762 --> 30:07.180
<i>I twist it.</i>

30:07.180 --> 30:07.973
Everything's
looking really good.

30:11.184 --> 30:12.519
Aye.

30:12.519 --> 30:14.396
It's come apart right here.

30:14.396 --> 30:16.023
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:16.023 --> 30:17.274
From here to here.

30:17.274 --> 30:18.233
Not--not a good thing.

30:18.233 --> 30:20.360
[bleep].

30:20.360 --> 30:22.112
Let's see if we can fix it.

30:22.112 --> 30:23.321
And I give it a twist.

30:23.321 --> 30:25.782
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:25.782 --> 30:28.326
And disaster has struck.

30:28.326 --> 30:30.787
It has come apart
in four different places.

30:30.787 --> 30:33.081
I'm very beside myself.

30:35.834 --> 30:37.294
Disaster struck.

30:37.294 --> 30:39.129
<i>I'm looking at the piece.</i>

30:39.129 --> 30:41.590
It has five to six separations.

30:41.590 --> 30:43.383
That's a heartbreaker.

30:43.383 --> 30:46.511
So you know what
you do with that.

30:46.511 --> 30:48.638
Mic drop.
You move on.

30:48.638 --> 30:50.932
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:50.932 --> 30:53.977
<i>- My plan right now</i>
<i>is to draw the line</i>

30:53.977 --> 30:55.062
<i>and then cut the lugs out.</i>

30:55.062 --> 30:57.481
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:57.481 --> 30:59.024
[bleep].

30:59.024 --> 31:01.193
<i>I got my measurements wrong.</i>

31:01.193 --> 31:04.196
So right now, my overall danger
with me cutting this

31:04.196 --> 31:06.698
is not having
enough steel in the middle

31:06.698 --> 31:09.826
to stretch out
to over two inches.

31:09.826 --> 31:12.829
I'm going to be somewhat narrow
in the middle,

31:12.829 --> 31:14.748
but, luckily, I'm thick,

31:14.748 --> 31:17.626
so I should be able
to spread it out.

31:17.626 --> 31:19.586
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:19.586 --> 31:22.839
Two steps forward
to go 50 steps backwards.

31:22.839 --> 31:24.341
"Forged in Fire."

31:24.341 --> 31:26.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:26.301 --> 31:30.055
- Today is crunch day,
the monumentous day.

31:30.055 --> 31:32.557
<i>My big concern is I have to</i>
<i>keep the blade at an even heat</i>

31:32.557 --> 31:35.977
and I have to be able
to hike myself up

31:35.977 --> 31:37.687
<i>to get it inside</i>
<i>the quench tank.</i>

31:37.687 --> 31:38.897
<i>Tall order.</i>

31:38.897 --> 31:40.607
[laughs]
Pun intended.

31:40.607 --> 31:42.651
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:42.651 --> 31:44.694
My forge is just too small.

31:44.694 --> 31:48.448
I'm still not getting the color
I need out of this blade.

31:48.448 --> 31:50.492
It's just not gonna get there.

31:50.492 --> 31:52.202
Think I'm just gonna
have to go for it.

31:52.202 --> 31:54.371
It's not even close.

31:54.371 --> 31:56.331
[bleep].

31:56.331 --> 31:57.874
<i>It's about as hot</i>
<i>as it's ever gonna get.</i>

31:57.874 --> 31:59.334
I don't think
I'm getting a second shot.

31:59.334 --> 32:01.002
<i>There's no pings.</i>

32:01.002 --> 32:02.337
<i>I'm still not sure</i>
<i>if it's hard enough.</i>

32:02.337 --> 32:04.339
Wow.

32:04.339 --> 32:06.633
Remarkably, the file sings.

32:06.633 --> 32:08.135
[scraping]

32:08.135 --> 32:09.344
It's hard.

32:09.344 --> 32:10.846
Rock and roll, baby.

32:10.846 --> 32:12.848
I'm rockin' this thing.

32:12.848 --> 32:17.310
<i>- The plan for day four</i>
<i>is to get this thing quenched.</i>

32:17.310 --> 32:19.104
Yesterday was
a pretty rough go.

32:19.104 --> 32:22.524
The horseshoe is gonna
end up being my guard.

32:22.524 --> 32:24.734
<i>Since I'm a ferrier, I figured</i>

32:24.734 --> 32:27.237
a handmade concave shoe
would look pretty slick.

32:27.237 --> 32:29.781
Cool.

32:29.781 --> 32:32.284
<i>Now I'm going to get my blade</i>
<i>a couple degrees hotter</i>

32:32.284 --> 32:34.327
than what I would want

32:34.327 --> 32:37.873
because of the trip between
my quench tank and my forges.

32:37.873 --> 32:42.127
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

32:42.127 --> 32:45.714
The sword of flame,
that's what I'm gonna call it.

32:45.714 --> 32:47.799
<i>I had to overcome</i>
<i>a lot of obstacles,</i>

32:47.799 --> 32:50.343
but all in all,
the quench went pretty good.

32:50.343 --> 32:52.220
<i>It's heavier</i>
<i>than I would like,</i>

32:52.220 --> 32:54.931
<i>but it's strong enough;</i>
<i>I don't think it'll break.</i>

32:54.931 --> 32:57.559
Whoo, done with forging!

32:57.559 --> 33:00.520
<i>- It's day five.</i>

33:00.520 --> 33:01.688
♪ Dun, dun, dun ♪

33:01.688 --> 33:04.316
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:04.316 --> 33:06.860
I feel I can get
the blade accomplished

33:06.860 --> 33:08.945
in the time I have left.

33:08.945 --> 33:11.573
<i>Pommel, handle, sharpen.</i>

33:13.158 --> 33:14.284
<i>I am so excited</i>
<i>to see the sword</i>

33:14.284 --> 33:15.785
<i>going into the challenges.</i>

33:15.785 --> 33:17.287
Okay.

33:17.287 --> 33:20.707
So now it's time
to do a weigh-in.

33:20.707 --> 33:23.168
Survey says...

33:23.168 --> 33:25.879
8.2 pounds.

33:25.879 --> 33:27.464
I can live with that.

33:27.464 --> 33:30.467
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33:30.467 --> 33:31.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:31.968 --> 33:33.970
- Todd, DJ, welcome back
to The Forge.

33:33.970 --> 33:36.223
You've both had five days
at your home forges

33:36.223 --> 33:38.141
to work on
your landsknecht swords.

33:38.141 --> 33:40.435
Todd, tell us about your blade.

33:40.435 --> 33:43.230
<i>- It's constructed</i>
<i>out of 5160.</i>

33:43.230 --> 33:45.065
<i>The handle</i>
<i>is traditional materials</i>

33:45.065 --> 33:46.316
<i>of wood with wrapped leather,</i>

33:46.316 --> 33:47.776
<i>and the pommel's assembled</i>

33:47.776 --> 33:50.070
<i>with a traditional</i>
<i>peened assembly.</i>

33:50.070 --> 33:53.031
- DJ, tell us about your blade.

33:53.031 --> 33:55.158
<i>- It's made out of 5160.</i>

33:55.158 --> 33:57.911
<i>I got a horseshoe</i>
<i>for the hand guard.</i>

33:57.911 --> 34:00.622
<i>I used mahogany</i>
<i>for the wood handle.</i>

34:00.622 --> 34:02.457
It was a hell of a build.

34:02.457 --> 34:04.209
- Well, gentlemen,
each of your blades

34:04.209 --> 34:06.378
will now be put through
a series of three tests.

34:06.378 --> 34:08.255
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

34:08.255 --> 34:09.839
and up first, the kill test.

34:09.839 --> 34:12.968
Doug?

34:12.968 --> 34:15.971
- Bladesmiths, the two-handed
German landsknecht sword's

34:15.971 --> 34:19.557
a big sword,
so we're expecting big damage.

34:19.557 --> 34:22.227
I will take your sword
and deliver slashes, thrusts,

34:22.227 --> 34:25.522
and chops
on this wild boar carcass.

34:25.522 --> 34:26.898
Todd, you're up first.
You ready?

34:26.898 --> 34:29.276
- Yes, I am.
- Let's do this.

34:29.276 --> 34:31.653
- My biggest concern
is the quench that I did.

34:31.653 --> 34:33.780
That's the make-or-break moment
of every weapon,

34:33.780 --> 34:35.740
and I'm not sure
if it was hot enough.

34:35.740 --> 34:37.659
My sword could break.

34:37.659 --> 34:40.537
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:40.537 --> 34:43.456
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

34:43.456 --> 34:50.255
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:04.644 --> 35:06.062
- All right, Todd.

35:06.062 --> 35:08.732
First up,
your handle construction.

35:08.732 --> 35:10.692
It's comfortable to hold onto.

35:10.692 --> 35:14.279
You have a very thick
and wide and stout edge,

35:14.279 --> 35:16.990
so it's a chopper,
not a slicer.

35:16.990 --> 35:21.536
The big issue I have with this
is that it's a heavy sword.

35:21.536 --> 35:23.872
But, despite its weight,
it will kill.

35:23.872 --> 35:25.624
- Yes.

35:25.624 --> 35:26.791
- All right, DJ,
it's your turn. You ready?

35:26.791 --> 35:28.251
- Yep.

35:28.251 --> 35:31.254
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

35:31.254 --> 35:38.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:38.303 --> 35:41.264
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

35:41.264 --> 35:48.188
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:00.075 --> 36:03.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:03.703 --> 36:06.331
- DJ, let's talk about
your sword here.

36:06.331 --> 36:08.208
It's even heavier
than the other sword.

36:08.208 --> 36:10.835
The tip you have over here
is wide.

36:10.835 --> 36:12.754
The first thrust went in.

36:12.754 --> 36:15.173
The second one couldn't,
and I tried.

36:18.093 --> 36:20.887
The one thing it did
was break its back.

36:20.887 --> 36:25.725
